 \u003Cstrong\u003Eparietal cells\u003C/strong\u003E of the gastric glands secrete hydrochloric acid and intrinsic factor, but not pepsinogen. \u003Cstrong\u003EChief cells\u003C/strong\u003E (also called zymogenic cells) are responsible for secreting both pepsinogen I and II. \u003Cstrong\u003EMucous neck cells\u003C/strong\u003E secrete only pepsinogen II along with mucus. \u003Cstrong\u003EG cells\u003C/strong\u003E secrete the hormone gastrin. \u003Cstrong\u003ESurface mucous cells\u003C/strong\u003E secrete protective mucus and bicarbonate.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EPepsinogen is the inactive precursor (zymogen) of pepsin, the main gastric protease. It is activated by hydrochloric acid in the gastric lumen to form pepsin, which then begins protein digestion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chief cells secrete both pepsinogen I and II, while mucous neck cells secrete only pepsinogen II","Pepsinogen is the inactive precursor of pepsin, the main gastric protease","Parietal cells secrete hydrochloric acid and intrinsic factor, not pepsinogen"],"references":["Johnson, L. R. (2018). Gastrointestinal Physiology E-Book: Gastrointestinal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","ISO 690 O\u0027Toole TJ, Sharma S. Physiology, Somatostatin. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538327/","Arnold R, H\u00fclst MV, Neuhof CH, Schwarting H, Becker HD, Creutzfeldt W. Antral gastrin-producing G-cells and somatostatin-producing D-cells in different states of gastric acid secretion. Gut. 1982 Apr;23(4):285-91. doi: 10.1136/gut.23.4.285. PMID: 6122629; PMCID: PMC1419730","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50622"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id"